Graphical abstract The aqueous all-3D-printed planar micro-supercapacitors is demonstrated through three-dimensional printing of the active electrode and LiCl/SiO2 water-in-salt electrolyte, showing a stable high voltage of 2 V, ultrahigh areal capacitance of 2381 mF cm−2 and areal energy density of 331 μWh cm−2. With the rapid development of integrated and miniaturized electronics, the planar energy storage devices with high capacitance and energy density are in enormous demand. Hence, the advanced manufacture and fast fabrication of microscale planar energy units are of great significance. Herein, we develop aqueous planar micro-supercapacitors (MSCs) with ultrahigh areal capacitance and energy density via an efficient all-3D-printing strategy, which can directly extrude the active material ink and gel electrolyte onto the substrate to prepare electrochemical energy storage devices. Both the printed active carbon/exfoliated graphene (AC/EG) electrode ink and electrolyte gel are highly processable with outstanding conductivity (~97 S cm−1 of electrode; ~34.8 mS cm−1 of electrolyte), thus benefiting the corresponding shaping and electrochemical performances. Furthermore, the 3D-printed symmetric MSCs can be operated stably at a high voltage up to 2.0 V in water-in-salt gel electrolyte, displaying ultrahigh areal capacitance of 2381 mF cm−2 and exceptional energy density of 331 μWh cm−2, superior to previous printed micro energy units. In addition, we can further tailor the integrated 3D-printed MSCs in parallel and series with various voltage and current outputs, enabling metal-free interconnection. Therefore, our all-3D-printed MSCs place a great potential in developing high-power micro-electronics fabrication and integration. Keywords 3D printing Micro-supercapacitors High-voltage Water-in-salt Graphene 1 Introduction The rapid development of printed and integrated micro-electronics, such as micro-sensors, micro-robots and implantable medical devices, has largely increased the demand for miniaturized electrochemical energy storage devices [1–5]. Among various types of micro energy units, micro-supercapacitors (MSCs) are preferable since they possess high power density, quick charge/discharge rate and ultralong cycling stability [6–9]. Until now, various technologies have been developed to prepare MSCs, such as electrochemical deposition [10–12], plasma etching [13], photolithography [14–16], vacuum filtration [17,18], screen printing [19–21] and inkjet printing [22–25]. However, such methods normally employed low mass loading of active materials on the microelectrodes of MSCs. Consequently, it resulted in relatively low areal capacitance and energy density, thus impeding further practicability. Therefore, more effective routes to design high-performance MSCs are required. 3D printing, usually known as an additive manufacturing technology, has been widely applied to fabricate energy storage devices in a simple, scalable and cost-effective way [26–30]. Compared to other methods, 3D printing can directly manufacture the 2D/3D devices in a discrete layer-by-layer additive manner [31–34]. In addition, 3D printing can accurately control the thickness of electrodes by increasing the mass loading of electrode materials, thereby improving the overall areal capacitances [35,36]. However, the energy density of the current 3D-printed MSCs is still low because of the low voltage of aqueous electrolyte, which was limited by the thermodynamic voltage window of 1.23 V before water decomposition [37,38]. Recently, water-in-salt (WIS) electrolytes, in which the salt weight and volume is greater than that of water [37], have been proposed to extend the stable electrochemical potential window of aqueous electrolyte greater than 3 V owing to nearly nonexistent of the free H2O molecules in WIS [39–41]. Hence, it is a better choice to fabricate all-3D-printed MSCs based on WIS electrolyte to enhance both high areal capacitance and energy density. In this work, we enabled the MSCs with remarkably high areal capacitance and energy density by 3D printing the active electrode and electrolyte. Notably, both of the prepared active varbon/exfoliated graphene (AC/EG) aqueous ink and LiCl/SiO2 electrolyte ink presented large viscosity and shear-thinning behavior, thus being applicable for 3D printing. More importantly, the as-fabricated 3D MSCs with five printed layers operated well at a high voltage of 2 V, thus providing an ultrahigh areal capacitance of 2381 mF cm−2 and unprecedented areal energy density of 331 μWh cm−2 as well as impressive capacitance retention about 80% for 10,000 cycles. In addition, such MSCs were feasible to multiple integration, thereby benefiting the voltage and capacity output regulation as well as validating metal-free interconnection. Therefore, our all-3D-printed MSCs are promising for next-generation of printed micro-electronics. 2 Experimental 2.1 Preparation of 3D-printable inks For the preparation of the printable active carbon (AC) ink, 0.05 g hydroxypropyl methyl cellulose (HPMC, 15000 mPa. s, Aladdin), 0.05 g hydroxyethyl cellulose (HEC, 80 ~ 125 mPa. s, Aladdin) and 0.5 g exfoliated graphene (EG) was first dispersed in deionized water (5 mL) and then transferred to water bath of 85 °C with continuous stirring for 30 min. After the formation of the uniformly concentrated dispersion, EG precursor ink was completed, in which both HPMC and HEC binders can endow appropriate rheological properties of the ink. With regard to AC printable ink, 0.1667 g AC (YP-80F, Kurary) was added into the above EG ink and fully mixed to prepare AC ink. The resultant AC ink composes of (solid content) 6.25 wt% of HPMC, 6.25 wt% of HEC, 62.5 wt% of EG, and 25 wt% of AC. EG used in this work was prepared by a popular method of electrochemical exfoliation of graphite, which was reported early [42]. 2.2 Fabrication of MSCs using 3D printing 3D printing was conducted on a benchtop robotic dispenser (ZZ-221, ZhongZhi Automation Co., Ltd.) and an air-powered fluid dispenser (JND983A) was adopted to control the ink flow rate. First, the desired pattern was designed using AutoCAD software and transferred to the robotic dispenser to control the motion of nozzles. Second, the prepared inks and gel electrolyte were housed in separate 30 mL syringes ready to be printed in sequence, and the inner diameter of the extruded needles for the electrode ink and electrolyte are 340 μm and 420 μm, respectively. Third, the typical printing speed and ink flow rate was set to 25 psi and 5 mm s−1 for AC ink, 10 psi and 3 mm s−1 for gel electrolyte. Subsequently, the robotic dispenser extruded the inks onto PET substrates according to the designed integrated patterns layer by layer to obtain electrodes with stacked-layer structure, and then the printed architectures were placed in a blast drying oven to remove the solvent and solidify the structure. Due to high conductivity, the inks could be directly used as electrodes without additional current collectors. After drying, the SiO2/LiCl gel electrolyte was extruded onto the project area between the micro electrodes and packaged by Kapton tape for electrochemical measurements. For comparison, EG ink was also printed into microelectrodes to fabricate EG symmetric MSCs named EG-MSCs, while other steps kept the same with AC-MSCs. Besides, we designed different graphics through CAD software and directly printed various structures based on those graphics, including integrated devices in parallel and series and so on. 2.3 Materials characterization The morphology characterization of EG and printed microelectrodes were acquired by transmission electron microscopy (TEM, JEM-2100) and scanning electron microscope (SEM, JSM-7800F). X-ray diffraction (XRD, Empyrean-100) and Raman spectroscopy (LabRAM HR 800) were also employed to characterize the structural properties of EG. The rheological properties of AC ink were obtained by a rheometer (DHR2, TA Instruments-Waters LLC) with 25 mm parallel plate geometry. A steady-state flow step was conducted from 103 to 10−3 s-1 in order to measure the viscosity of AC ink at different shear rate. Peak hold step was carried out at three different shear rates in three time-intervals to obtain time-viscosity curve. A stress sweep from 100-104 Pa was also conducted at a constant frequency of 1 Hz in order to record the storage and loss moduli variations as functions of the sweep stress. Four-point probe equipment (RTS-9) and conductivity meter (DDS-11A) was conducted to measure the conductivity of AC/EG ink and gel electrolyte ink respectively. The nitrogen adsorption–desorption analysis was carried out by a physical adsorption meter (evo, Quadrasorb) at −196 ℃, and the specific surface area of 3D printed electrode was calculated through Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) method. Before the measurement, the sample was degassed at 200 ℃ for 4 hours. 2.4 Electrochemical measurement The electrochemical performance of the fabricated MSCs was evaluated by cycle voltammetry (CV) measurements with different scan rates from 5 to 50 mV s−1, galvanostatic charge-discharge (GCD) profiles performed at current densities from 0.25 to 5 mA cm−2, and electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) plots tested in the frequency range from 0.01 Hz to 100 kHz with a 5 mV AC amplitude via an electrochemical workstation (CHI 760E). Cycling stability of AC-MSCs was tested using a LANHE-M340A battery test system. 3 Results 3.1 3D printing fabrication of AC-MSCs The fabrication process of 3D printed electrodes and electrolyte with interdigital configuration is schematically illustrated in Fig. 1 a. Before printing, an electrode ink was prepared by uniformly mixing AC, highly conductive EG and polymer binders in aqueous system. High-quality EG was synthesized by electrochemical exfoliation [42], with the layer number of less than 10 (Fig. S1). Then, a water-in-salt (WIS) electrolyte consisting of 20 M LiCl and SiO2 nanospheres was employed to form printable gel electrolyte. The prepared electrode and electrolyte inks were then separately transferred into two syringes with different diameters for 3D printing. The AC ink was directly printed onto the PET substrate from the designed interdigitated pattern (Fig. S2), which exhibited four fingers through a program-controlled 3D printer to construct a close stacked multilayer electrode. Subsequently, the electrolyte ink was extruded to the space between the fabricated electrodes. Thus, the all-3D-printed AC-MSCs were successfully constructed. Furthermore, mask-free multi-shaped devices can be available from computer designed graphics by 3D printing, e.g., interdigital shape (Fig. 1b), five parallelly-connected devices (Fig. 1c), five serially-connected devices (Fig. 1d), parallel strip (Fig. 1e), concentric circle (Fig. 1f) and a letter-shaped “DICP” (Fig. 1g). Remarkably, even under twisting and bending, the microelectrodes could retain the structural integrity without any fragmentation and brittleness, indicative of excellent mechanical flexibility and good adhesion between electrodes and substrates. 3.2 Rheological properties of inks and morphology of AC microelectrodes The rheological properties of inks played an important role on the structure and performance of printed devices. Therefore, a rheological study of the AC and electrolyte inks was conducted to probe their compatibility for extrusion-based 3D printing (Fig. 2 a-c). Fig. 2a shows the viscosities of AC and electrolyte inks as a function of shear rate. Both of their viscosities rapidly decreased with increasing shear rates, exhibiting a typical shear-thinning behavior of non-Newtonian fluids. This result strongly indicated the excellent printability of the AC and electrolyte inks. To further characterize the rheological properties of the prepared inks, stress sweep step studies were tested at a frequency of 1 Hz. The yield stress at the mutation point between storage modulus (G′) and loss modulus (G″) of AC and electrolyte inks is ~ 400 and 6300 Pa (Fig. 2b), respectively. At the plateau region of below yield point (G′ > G″), the two inks predominantly displayed solid-like behavior, while a liquid-like behavior (G′ < G″) was observed at the region of larger than yield point. The high yield points enabled continuous extrusion through micrometer-sized nozzles and immediate solidification. Peak hold step , which could simulate the extruding process of 3D printing, was measured by imposing alternate low (0.1 s−1) and high (100 s−1) shear rates of the inks. As shown in Fig. 2c, the viscosity sharply drops when the shear rate switched from 0.1 to 100 s−1 and the instantaneous recovery of viscosity occurred when the shear rate returned to 0.1 s−1, showing the potential for continuous extrusion, which is necessary in the 3D printing process. Similarly, the EG ink also exhibited outstanding shear-thinning behavior, thus affording the extrusion through nozzles under certain shear force (Fig. S3). Due to the excellent printing performance of inks, we successfully printed 3D-architecture MSCs by extruding the AC inks with multilayer electrodes, which were denoted as AC-MSC-x (x = 1,2,3,4,5), where x designated the number of AC-based electrode layers. Fig. 2d-f displayed side-view SEM images of AC-MSC-5 with an average thickness of about 200 μm for each layer (Fig. 2d), approximately closed to the single layer thickness of AC-MSC-2,3,4 (Fig. 2g-i), suggestive of the uniform printability of 3D-printed microelectrodes. Besides, it could be observed that the EG flakes in the printed electrode presented an interconnectedly stacked structure and thus built a conductive network, facilitating the transportation and collection of electrons. In the printed electrode, AC were tightly adhered to the EG flakes, and evenly distributed in the electrode. The inner structures were shown in Fig. S4, similar with the architecture shown in Fig. 2f. Hence, it demonstrated the isotropy of microstructure of AC electrodes. Moreover, the electrical conductivity of the printed AC microelectrode on the PET substrates was ~97 S cm−1 (Fig. S5), highlighting the stable electron transport channels in all directions even when the electrodes were thick. 3.3 Electrochemical performance of AC-MSC-1 To demonstrate the electrochemical performance of the printed electrodes, a 20 M LiCl gel electrolyte with electrical conductivity of ~34.8 mS cm−1 was prepared and printed onto the interdigital microelectrodes (Fig. 3 a and Fig. S6). The electrochemically stable potential of electrolyte, which critically affected the electrochemical performance of MSCs, was investigated by using linear sweep voltammetry (LSV, Fig. 3b) analysis at 10 mV s−1. The highly concentrated electrolyte showed visible cathodic and anodic currents when the potential reached −1.45 and 1.25 V vs. Ag/AgCl electrode, respectively, suggesting a stable and wide voltage window of 2.7 V. Furthermore, we carried out the CV measurements of AC-MSC-1 with different cut-off voltage at a scan rate of 2 mV s−1 to evaluate the appropriate voltage window for AC-MSCs. As shown in Fig. 3c, the polarization phenomenon of AC-MSC-1 was observed when the voltage was over 2.0 V. Meanwhile, AC-MSC-1 under the voltage range of 0–2.2 V was unstable for a long cycle test (Fig. S7). Therefore, the voltage range of AC-MSCs was selected from 0 to 2 V. Electrochemical performance of AC-MSC-1 with 20 M LiCl gel electrolyte was further evaluated by GCD profiles tested at current densities from 0.5 to 1.5 mA cm−2 (Fig. 3d), CV curves with various scan rates (Fig. S8b) and EIS plot (Fig. S8a). AC-MSC-1 working at 2 V exhibited approximately rectangular CV curves, and nearly symmetrical triangle GCD profiles, suggestive of the electrical double-layer capacitive (EDLC) effect. From a comparison of CV curves (Fig. 3e) at a scan rate of 10 mV s−1, it can be seen that the AC-MSC-1 displayed higher integrated area than the MSCs from the pure EG ink without active material of AC (denoted as EG-MSC-1). The areal capacitance calculated according the discharged profiles (Fig. 3d, Fig. S9a) was shown in Fig. 3f, and the AC-MSC-1 exhibited an areal capacitance of 458 mF cm−2 at a current density of 0.5 mA cm−2 while that of EG-MSC-1 was only 60.7 mF cm−2. The results therefore manifested that the main capacity contribution of AC-MSCs originated from AC while the EG was employed to construct conductive network in microelectrodes. Remarkably, AC-MSC-1 showed satisfactory rate performance as well, delivering a capacitance of 222 mF cm−2 even at 5 mA cm−2. In addition, AC-MSC-1 exhibited long-term stable cycling with an extraordinary capacitance retention of 78.9% after 10,000 cycles at 2.5 mA cm−2 (Fig. 3g). 3.4 Electrochemical performance of AC-MSCs In order to increase the loading of active materials, AC-MSC-x (x = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5) with multilayers were printed. Fig. 4 a-f display the optical images of the AC-MSCs printed on PET substrate, and as mentioned above, the electrode thickness increased as the 3D-printed layers increased in multiples. Notably, the similar rectangle-like CV curves of AC-MSCs were exhibited in Fig. 4g with varying currents. Fig. 4h demonstrates the GCD profiles of AC-MSCs with different electrodes layers obtained at the uniform current density of 0.5 mA cm−2, and all AC-MSCs displayed the almost symmetrical triangle-shape curves. Normally, the areal capacitance increased with the printed layers increment, and the AC-MSC-5 delivered the highest areal capacitance of 2381 mF cm−2 at current density of 0.5 mA cm−2, higher than AC-MSC-1 (458 mF cm−2), AC-MSC-2 (1020 mF cm−2), AC-MSC-3 (1560 mF cm−2), AC-MSC-4 (1988 mF cm−2) (Fig. 4j). However, the rate capability became worse as the printed electrode layers increases (Fig. 4i and Figs. S10−14). For example, the gravimetric capacity of AC-MSCs-1 is 24.6 F g−1 at 0.11 A g−1 and 11.9 F g−1 at 1.1 A g−1, while for AC-MSCs-5, the gravimetric capacitance is 25.1 F g−1 at 0.02 A g−1 and 11.6 F g−1 at 0.21 A g−1. For the microdevices, the series resistance significantly increases with increment of the electrodes thickness, leading to a sluggish charge/discharge kinetics, thereby weakening the rate performance. In contrast, the volumetric capacitances showed minor differences, attributing to interconnected EG sheets that provided abundant pathways for electrons and ions transfer within pore structure (Fig. S15). Importantly, Ragone plot showed in Fig. 4k compared the areal energy and power densities of our AC-based MSCs with other planar MSCs. Remarkably, our AC-MSC-5 presented an ultrahigh areal energy density of 331 μWh cm−2 at 0.5 mW cm−2, superior to those previously reported MSCs, such as MXene-MnONW//MXene-MnONW (19.2 µWh cm−2) [1], AC//AC (120 µWh cm−2) [8], PPy@rGO//PEDOT@rGO (4.3 μWh cm−2) [15], RuO2//RuO2 (91.4 μWh cm−2) [43], 3D-printed V2O5/rGO//G–VNQDs/rGO (73.9 μWh cm−2) [44], 3D-printed MXene//MXene (24.4 μWh cm−2) [45], and 3D-printed V2O5/SWCNT//VN/SWCNT (41.28 μWh cm−2) [46]. Thus, the results corroborate that 3D-printing can offer a new avenue for achieving the manufacture of energy storage devices with extraordinary energy density and capacitance. In order to realize the integrated circuits with the high voltage and high capacity, AC-MSCs arrays in parallel (Fig. 5 a) and series (Fig. 5b) configurations were fabricated by direct 3D-printing. Because of the excellent electrical conductance and electrochemical performance, the AC ink as microelectrodes can be interconnected with AC-MSCs without additional metal-based contacts. It was observed that the CV curves (Fig. 5c) of AC-MSCs connected in series exhibited nearly rectangular shapes illustrating a typical EDLC behavior, and correspondingly the working voltage showed a linear increase from 2 V for single cell to 6 V for three cells and 10 V for five cells. The boosted voltage behavior was also validated in GCD profiles (Fig. 5d) with almost the same charge–discharge time, linearly increasing voltage and decreasing capacitance. It therefore showed an outstanding uniform performance of 3D-printed AC-MSCs (Fig. S16a). Furthermore, parallel connection can effectively enhance the output capacitance. As shown in Fig. 5e and f, the voltage of AC-MSCs connected from 1 to 5 devices in parallel fashion remained unchanged and the capacitance increased in proportion as well (Fig. S16b). Remarkably, four serially-connected concentric-shape MSCs can easily lighten the logo of DICP (Fig. 5g) for ~ 3 min, consisted of 42 light-emitting diodes (LEDs), further highlighting the practical potential of 3D-printed AC-MSCs as scalable microscale power units. In addition, the AC-MSC-1 also exhibited an acceptable flexibility under bending state (Fig. S17). 4 Conclusion In summary, we have demonstrated an all-3D-printing strategy to construct interdigital MSCs through exploiting an aqueous AC-based electrode ink and a LiCl/SiO2 WIS gel electrolyte ink with excellent rheological properties and electrochemical performance. Interconnect EG sheets served as 3D hosts for concordantly accommodating the active materials of AC for electron transporting, and the self-supported AC/EG electrodes with porous architecture provided a fast ion transport pathway, thus boosting the electrochemical performance including rate capability and capacitance. As a result, the aqueous all-printed planar AC-MSCs with a stable work voltage of 2 V possessed ultrahigh areal capacitance of 2381 mF cm−2 and energy density of 331 μWh cm−2, significantly higher than other aqueous planar MSCs previously reported. Therefore, this work has demonstrated the feasibility and applicability of extrusion-based 3D printing for high-performance electrochemical energy storage devices. coredata.dc:description: With the rapid development of integrated and miniaturized electronics, the planar energy storage devices with high capacitance and energy density are in enormous demand. Hence, the advanced manufacture and fast fabrication of microscale planar energy units are of great significance. Herein, we develop aqueous planar micro-supercapacitors (MSCs) with ultrahigh areal capacitance and energy density via an efficient all-3D-printing strategy, which can directly extrude the active material ink and gel electrolyte onto the substrate to prepare electrochemical energy storage devices. Both the printed active carbon/exfoliated graphene (AC/EG) electrode ink and electrolyte gel are highly processable with outstanding conductivity (~97 S cm−1 of electrode; ~34.8 mS cm−1 of electrolyte), thus benefiting the corresponding shaping and electrochemical performances. Furthermore, the 3D-printed symmetric MSCs can be operated stably at a high voltage up to 2.0 V in water-in-salt gel electrolyte, displaying ultrahigh areal capacitance of 2381 mF cm−2 and exceptional energy density of 331 μWh cm−2, superior to previous printed micro energy units. In addition, we can further tailor the integrated 3D-printed MSCs in parallel and series with various voltage and current outputs, enabling metal-free interconnection. Therefore, our all-3D-printed MSCs place a great potential in developing high-power micro-electronics fabrication and integration.
